## Runtime-replaceable platform defaults

MemoryProvider / ThreadPool / Clock ship as monomorphised trait
bounds. Default no_os / std implementations are intended to live in
the engine crate; this crate stays platform-agnostic. Consumer
override is via the scheduler builder, not via dyn.

## Scheduling hint tuple specialisation

`SchedulingHint = (Urgency, Divisibility, Significance)` uses a sealed
trait on tuples. A future change could expose a builder-style API
(`.immediate().atomic().critical()`) if consumer ergonomics surface
as a friction point. Today's tuple form matches the rest of the
compile-time composition model (AccessSet, WorkUnit generics).

## ColumnValue specialisation coverage

The blanket `min_specialization` default covers every `Copy + 'static`
type via `size_of::<Self>() * 8`. arvo sub-byte types (UFixed<1, 0>,
UFixed<2, 0>, etc.) need explicit specialisation to report their
non-byte BIT_WIDTH. This crate ships with a handful of specialisations
matching arvo's concrete aliases; additional arvo widths (if arvo
ever adds them) need follow-up specialisations here.

## Non-engine post-review notes

### `WorkUnit::Ctx` carries all 7 provider bounds unconditionally

Every WorkUnit's `Ctx` associated type requires the full provider
bound set (`HasEach + HasBatch + HasReduce +
HasMemoryProvider + HasThreadPool + HasClock + HasWorker`, or the
current equivalent) regardless of which iteration APIs the WU
actually uses. Two possible follow-ups:

- Per-method bound splitting, e.g. `fn execute_each` bounded only
 by `HasEach`, `fn execute_batch` only by `HasBatch`, etc. Each
 WU declares which iteration methods it implements and only
 those pay the bound cost.
- Document the blanket no-op impl pattern for unused APIs on
 provider tuples, so a WU that only wants Each can still satisfy
 HasBatch / HasReduce with a provider that no-ops.

Design decision deferred until a concrete WU surfaces friction.

### EachApi / BatchApi / ReduceApi all name method `run()`

At any call site on a provider tuple implementing all three,
fully-qualified syntax is required
(`<P as EachApi>::run(...)`). Ergonomic friction. Consider
renaming to `run_each` / `run_batch` / `run_reduce`. Breaking
change; holds until a separate signal (or a deliberate breaking
round on the api crate).

### HasMemoryProvider / HasThreadPool / HasClock accessor naming

The three bounds ship accessor methods `memory()` / `threads()` /
`clock()`, which don't match whatever the `provider!` macro would
generate from the trait name (e.g. a macro-derived accessor might
be `memory_provider()` / `thread_pool()` / `clock()`). Either
document the asymmetry or rename for consistency. Both options
require touching every consumer; defer to a breaking round.

