## Type-level dedup on Concat

AccumRead and AccumWrite carry duplicates by design at round-4.
Logical dedup via `#[marker] Contains` makes duplicates correctness-
irrelevant: the trait solver picks any matching occurrence and
stops. Trait-solver chain length grows linearly with duplicate
count; not pathological at the validated depth-5 / 25-WU scale
(0.53s wall clock, ~36-element chain for 13 distinct stores).

Physical dedup is research-deferred. The naive `ConcatDedup<R>`
shape (skip-if-contained vs prepend-if-absent) hits the same E0119
coherence wall as round-3's NotIn proof; round-4's M2 sketch at
`mock/research/sketches/202605050800_dedup_concat/FINDINGS.md`
captures the failure modes. Path forward: either `feature(specialization)`
stabilises to a usable subset, or a coherence-clean alternative
encoding surfaces. Round-5+ scope.

## Bitset-backed AccessSet fallback

If `feature(marker_trait_attr)` becomes unviable (rustc removes or
restricts marker-trait coherence; cross-crate marker resolution
shifts), the AccessSet machinery redesigns as a compile-time
bitset over a per-app StoreIndex ConstParamTy. Shape sketched in
`mock/research/marker_trait_attr_bitset_fallback.md`. Not built
in round-4; documented as the planned response. Triggered by a
concrete signal that the keystone is breaking; otherwise stays in
research.

## HasTrivialCtor consumer-side adoption

The Provider unification round (202605091700) introduced
`HasTrivialCtor` on notko and impls it on the four scheduler
wrappers (`Resource<T>`, `Column<T>`, `Virtual<T>`,
`LinkedBin<T: ?Sized>`). Downstream substrate crates (arvo,
vehje, viola) may impl `HasTrivialCtor` on their own marker
types as a usability nicety so consumers can reach for
`.with(MyMarker::new())` consistently. Not load-bearing; the
`.with(value)` shape works through `Provider::Init` regardless.
Cross-repo opportunity tracked here.

## Wire Resource::new to the scheduler-owned resource registry

`Resource::new(value: T)` currently consumes the value but drops
it at construction. The function is a stub-time placeholder until
HILA-RUNTIME-C6 ships the persistence spine. The drop matches the
prior `add_resource(_init: T)` semantics on `SchedulerBuilder`;
the type-level role of `Resource<T>` as a registration marker is
unchanged. Decision rationale captured in
`mock/research/notes/202605091700_src_apply_decisions.md` (D1).

When C6 lands, the constructor will route the value into
scheduler-owned storage via the persistence layer. Revisit
`hilavitkutin-api/src/store.rs` `Resource::new` and update the
doc comment when the data plane is the actual home. Consumers
reading the current doc-comment about the drop should not see
behaviour change post-C6 except that the value is now retained.

